VGUDIPOODI SRIHARIThe two proved a great vocal combination once again in their jugalbandi, complementing each other.The jugalbandi of Carnatic and Hindustani styles by Sriram Parasuram and his wife Anoorada marked the impressive closure of South Indian Cultural Association's 46th annual cultural festival at Lalitha Kala Thoranam. This was the last programme of the festival.Sriram Parasuram, who was a child prodigy with violin, has mastered the Hindustani system too and is a fine vocalist.Anoorada too is a vocalist in both the Indian styles. She is also a playback singer of south Indian cinema. The two proved a great vocal combination once again in their jugalbandi, complementing each other.Sriram opened the show with analapinHamsadhwani,a commonragain both the systems. Sriram did it in Hindusthani style and Anoorada continued in Carnatic, giving the taste of each of these styles. Dikshitar'sVatapiwas the choice composition.Swara Prastharawas an attraction. Sriram then went for aTaranain Hindustani inMadhya layaandDhrut laya, followed by a briefSargam. Sreenivasa Rao on violin, D S R Murthy on mridangam for the Carnatic system and Javed Najmuddin on tabla and Balwant Kulkarni on harmonium for Hindustani, accompanied them.They presented Manohari Raga, that is Kamala Manohari forNee Muddu Momu. Sriram then rendered Hindustani ragaMisra Tilakkamod, followed by athumri Rasiyaon Radha-Krishna theme.Poorvi Kalyaniin Carnatic for aJawaliandPooriyain Hindusthani for aThumrimarked the end part of Jugalbandi.MarugelarainJayantasriin -Desadi Thalam- common for both. The percussion solo between mridangam and tabla turned out to be another treat.On the previous day, T. N. Seshagopalan figured in a pleasing Carnatic vocal with a well-chosen repertoire. A rareGangeyabhushaniforEvvare Nee Sari, andBhairaviforTanayuni Brovawere notable numbers from him.Bottom Template Starts
